prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Band 7 continuum
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: In these ~4 min integrations we will detect the dust emission in our sample galaxies.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: The correlator set up is what is needed to perform the observations which is simply just imaging.
The angular resolution of 1 arcsec is sufficient for a detection of 1 mm flux within these galaxies.

We require a rms limit of 0.1 mJy for a typical 0.5 mJy detection. This is deep enough to detect a gas mass of a few 10**10 up to z=3 for our sample. This requires a total integration time of 4.5 minutes. We have predicted gas masses for our galaxies and from this calculate that nearly all samples should have a gas mass detection several times this limit. To reach an rms of 0.1 rms and including overheads brings our program to 4.72 hours. All of our observations will be at 345 GHz with a bandwidth of 7.5 GHz. This will ensure that we can carry out our science goals even for the most gas depeleted galaxies.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: How galaxies get their baryons to produce star formation is a major question in extragalactic astronomy. The solution to this during the peak epoch of galaxy formation at 1 < z < 3 appears to be through a mixture of: in-situ star formation, gas brought in through mergers, and the still mysterious process of gas accretion. However, these results are based on estimates of galaxy cold masses using the inverse Schmidt-Kennicutt law. Observations with ALMA of an abundance matched sample of massive galaxies at 1 < z < 3 in the CANDELS UDS field will allow a direct determination of the cold gas masses within these systems. By using this abundance matched sample we can then infer the methods these baryons are assembled. We can do this as the merging and star formation history of these galaxies is already well established, thereby allowing us to quantify accurately the role of gas accretion in the formation of galaxies during the epoch of peak galaxy formation.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Cosmology and the High Redshift Universe
